of England</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole></gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:personRoles><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/55291222-B591-47C2-982E-45A8B7796722"><gtr:id>55291222-B591-47C2-982E-45A8B7796722</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Colin</gtr:firstName><gtr:otherNames>Ronald</gtr:otherNames><gtr:surname>Talbot</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FF003749%2F1"><gtr:id>FD395F7A-DDDC-4D09-B8A8-CCF3DFE65015</gtr:id><gtr:title>Theories of Performance</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/F003749/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>Theories of Performance Many of the projects in the ESRC Public Services research programme have addressed different aspects of performance in the public sector. Some have looked at how performance is measured and the problems this entails, especially when trying to draw overall conclusions through mechanisms like league tables or star-ratings. Other have looked at how managers and leaders in public organisations deal with issues of performance, including failure. Another group of projects have focussed mainly on the external influences on public organisations that may (or may not) help to shape their performance. Finally, a group of projects has looked at the 'bottom-line'&amp;nbsp;- has all of the above led to real improvements in outputs and outcomes? &lt;/p>

&lt;p>The purpose of this Research Fellowship is to take a step back from this detailed research and look at the bigger picture and ask two fundamental questions: &lt;/p>

&lt;ol>
 

 &lt;li>What do we know, from the ESRC projects and other sources, about the nature of performance in public organisations&amp;nbsp;- do we have a viable theory of public organisational peformance?; &lt;/li>

 &lt;li>Do we have a robust understanding&amp;nbsp;- a theory or theories&amp;nbsp;- of what sort of external interventions best improve performance? &lt;/li>
